#X text 497 126 Note also how [print] ignores the 'float' selector \, as well as the 'list' selector when the first element is a float - this reinforces the idea that these selectors should be implicit., f 62;
#X msg 644 264 list 4;
#X text 698 264 becomes a float;
#X obj 622 360 print;
#X text 497 31 Conceptually \, a list message containing just one float is the same as a float message. In the same way \, a list containing just a symbol is the same as a symbol message. Finally \, an empty list is conceptually the same as a bang message. Pd treats these special cases of lists as such. One good example is the [print] object., f 62;
#X text 49 19 A message selector is the first symbol in a message and defines its data type. The special types (the most common messages that Pd objects understand) are: float \, symbol \, list \, bang and pointer (this one used for data structures only). A bang is a special message type that is used as a control trigger \, so it has its own special selector. The "float" selector doesn't need to be specified and neither does "list" if its first element is a float. Other message selectors can be anything else defined by the user as objects in Pd can also deal with other message types. If a message contains only one symbol \, like "stop" \, it is considered a selector with no actual message attached.;
